<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF109-831-267  </DOCNO><DOCID>09 831 267.andM;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Newsbytes  May 8 1990* Full Text COPYRIGHT Newsbytes Inc. 1990.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>IBM announces CFC emission lowering. (chlorofluorocarbon)</TITLE><AUTHOR>McMullen, Barbara E.; McMullen, John F.andM;</AUTHOR><DESCRIPT>Company:   International Business Machines Corp. (Environmental policy).andO;Ticker:    IBM.andO;Topic:     Computer industryChlorofluorocarbonsEnvironmental ProtectionComputer Manufacture.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>IBM ANNOUNCES CFC EMISSION LOWERING ARMONK, NEW YORK, U.S.A., 1990 MAY 4 (NB)-- IBM has announced that chlorofluorocarbon (CFC) emissions from IBMmanufacturing sites in the U.S.andP;  were reduced 37 percent in 1989 from their1988 levels.andM;This reduction represents a 54% reduction since 1987 when the company'sCFC-elimination program began and continues IBM towards its stated goal ofeliminating all CFC use in its products and processes by the end of 1993.andM;IBM also announced that, on a worldwide basis, IBM achieved a 21 percentreduction in emissions for 1989 over 1988 and a cumulative reduction of 35percent since 1987.andM;CFCs are believed to be a significant contributor to the depletion of theozone layer in the earth's upper atmosphere, which screens out much of thesun's harmful ultraviolet radiation.andP;  They have been the subject ofinternational agreements to eliminate their use and IBM states that itsschedule for 1993 elimination is several years ahead of any deadlines underthese agreements.andM;IBM also announced that it had made substantial reductions in its emissionsof methyl chloroform which is also believed to affect the ozone layer.andP;  Byyear-end 1989, the company's emissions of methyl chloroform had been lowered70 percent from 1987, an IBM statement said.andM;(Barbara E. McMullen andamp; John F. McMullen/19900505/Press Contact: Mac Jeffery,IBM, (914) 765-6443.)andO;</TEXT></DOC>